10:54.353 --> 10:58.858 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Is there any rational
explanation, any explanation
you can think of for doing that?

10:58.891 --> 11:07.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: Well, I guess a
benign explanation
was simply an outreach to the
Russians, the

11:07.066 --> 11:08.034 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Russian government.

11:08.067 --> 11:11.537 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So that's not, in and of itself,
untoward.

11:11.570 --> 11:21.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, again, not knowing the
intent or the
content, and whether or not the
sort of time-honored

11:21.180 --> 11:28.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
principle of one president at a
time in this
country, that did give rise,
particularly

11:28.054 --> 11:40.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
given the attempts to mask,
apparently, this
dialogue, so that was certainly
a concern

11:40.099 --> 11:41.067 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to all of us.

11:41.100 --> 11:42.868 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It certainly was to me
personally.

11:42.902 --> 11:48.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Can you think of
a reason why
it would be necessary to have a
secret -- a

11:48.708 --> 11:52.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
channel that was secret from
U.S. intelligence
agencies?

11:52.311 --> 11:55.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: Well, if it's
true -- and,
again, I'm not -- I can't
confirm or deny

11:55.848 --> 12:02.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- but if it's true that the
objective here
was to use Russian secure
communications as

12:02.888 --> 12:13.799 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the mode of this dialogue or
this communication,
that is, I will say, curious.

12:13.833 --> 12:16.736 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why all the cloak-and-dagger
secrecy?

12:16.769 --> 12:26.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If the intent was simply to
reach out to establish
-- to make acquaintance -- but
one wonders

12:26.912 --> 12:30.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if there was something worse
than that or
more nefarious than that.

12:30.850 --> 12:35.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, again, we didn't know, I
certainly didn't
know before I left the
government on the 20th

12:35.588 --> 12:37.356 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of January.

12:37.389 --> 12:40.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I'm asking
because yesterday
-- or, over the weekend, the
secretary of

12:40.292 --> 12:45.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
homeland security, John Kelly,
said in an
interview, he said, it's a good
thing.

12:45.097 --> 12:48.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said, if there were attempts
to open lines
of communication, it's a good
thing.

12:48.968 --> 12:50.970 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's a positive thing.

12:51.003 --> 12:54.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: Well, it could
be, and I agree
with him.

12:54.573 --> 12:57.176 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, again, this is not a new
thing.

12:57.209 --> 13:04.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Other governments have sought
back channels,
and particularly as
administrations change

13:04.650 --> 13:06.318 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
over.

13:06.352 --> 13:12.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there is an art form here to
how this
is done, and there is a line
between reaching

13:12.358 --> 13:17.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out, establishing lines of
communication,
vs. substantively undermining
the policies

13:17.763 --> 13:19.131 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the current administration.

13:19.165 --> 13:22.902 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And, again, we do have a
principle here of
one president at a time.

13:22.935 --> 13:29.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I want to ask you
about two
recent disclosures of classified
information

13:29.308 --> 13:31.110 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
by the president himself.

13:31.143 --> 13:35.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One was in a meeting with
Russian officials
in the Oval Office when the
president shared

13:35.848 --> 13:39.051 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
information about ISIS
capabilities...

13:39.084 --> 13:40.886 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JAMES CLAPPER: Right.

13:40.920 --> 13:44.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: ... that had all
the earmarks
of coming from Israeli
intelligence, and then

13:44.123 --> 13:48.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
separately in a conversation
with the president
of the Philippines, when the
president said

13:49.028 --> 13:53.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that two U.S. nuclear subs had
been in the
vicinity of North Korea.

13:53.699 --> 13:57.436 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Is this truly damaging
information to share,
or is all this overblown?

13:57.469 --> 14:02.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: Well, certainly,
I guess there
are two dimensions to this.

14:02.341 --> 14:08.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One, the public revelation of
this, which,
of course, was in both cases
somehow leaked

14:09.014 --> 14:13.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the media, that -- and leaks,
I have to
say, are bad.

14:13.853 --> 14:21.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I know that's the lifeblood of
the media business,
but, for the intelligence
community, leaks

14:21.827 --> 14:23.729 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
are bad.

14:23.762 --> 14:28.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They compromise sources and
methods, tradecraft,
in some cases, can endanger the
lives of assets.

14:28.734 --> 14:31.704 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, leaks are damaging.

14:31.737 --> 14:38.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other dimension, of course,
is the revelation
of these things to a foreign
government.

14:38.711 --> 14:47.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, that kind of thing goes on
all the time,
but it's also in due deference
to protecting

14:47.152 --> 14:52.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
either the operational equities
or the intelligence
equities.

14:52.925 --> 14:55.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's not something you just
kind of wing
extemporaneously.

14:55.661 --> 15:01.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: These incidents
must give some
in the intelligence community
pause.

15:01.700 --> 15:03.769 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: I'm sure it does.

15:03.802 --> 15:05.671 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And it's not exactly
confidence-building.

15:05.704 --> 15:15.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that's important to
restore or
achieve a level of confidence
that that flow

15:15.147 --> 15:16.882 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
can continue unabated.

15:16.916 --> 15:21.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What do you hear
from your
friends in the intelligence
community about

15:21.287 --> 15:23.222 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
their view of President Trump?

15:23.255 --> 15:32.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: I think the view
of the intelligence
community, as much as I
explained to him when

15:32.231 --> 15:37.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I spoke with him by phone on the
11th of January,
after he characterized the
intelligence community

15:37.069 --> 15:43.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as Nazis, that the national
intelligence community
is a national treasure, and that
the men of

15:43.842 --> 15:49.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the women of the community stand
ready to
support the president, whoever
it is, particularly

15:49.748 --> 15:51.417 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in his role as commander in
chief.

15:51.450 --> 15:53.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The terrorist
threat.

15:53.886 --> 15:57.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Over the last few days, the
secretary of homeland
security, John Kelly, has
painted a pretty

15:57.957 --> 16:00.092 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
frightening picture.

16:00.125 --> 16:05.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said at one point he expects
-- quote -- "a
lot more attacks" like the one
in Manchester,

16:05.464 --> 16:06.832 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
England.

16:06.865 --> 16:09.201 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he said: "The terror threat
is worse than
most people realize.

16:09.234 --> 16:12.538 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If people knew what I knew, they
would never
leave the house in the morning."

16:12.571 --> 16:14.273 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Do you share...

16:14.306 --> 16:19.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: And he went on to
praise the
counterterrorism efforts that we
have under

16:19.211 --> 16:26.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
way, of course, very much of
which the intelligence
community is involved in.

16:26.118 --> 16:32.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have gone to great
lengths and made
great investments to try to
ensure that we

16:32.758 --> 16:38.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
don't have a similar instance as
happened
in Manchester.

16:38.931 --> 16:44.903 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I would point out that this
may not necessarily
come from outside.

16:44.937 --> 16:48.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the issues we have had in
this country
have been caused by U.S.
citizens.

16:48.574 --> 16:52.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you share that
level of
alarm, though, that people
wouldn't leave

16:52.144 --> 16:53.779 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
their houses if they knew...

16:53.812 --> 16:57.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: Well, I'm here,
so I left my
house this morning.

16:57.850 --> 17:00.753 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: North Korea.

17:00.786 --> 17:05.257 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Do you believe there's a
realistic chance
now that North Korea could pull
back from

17:05.290 --> 17:07.993 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
its nuclear weapons development
program?

17:08.027 --> 17:14.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: I think it's
unlikely, and
I certainly think it's not
realistic for us

17:14.800 --> 17:19.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to expect the North Koreans to
give up their
nuclear weapons.

17:19.838 --> 17:22.241 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That is their ticket to
survival.

17:22.274 --> 17:30.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was taken aback when I visited
North Korea
in November 2014 to bring out
two of our citizens

17:30.115 --> 17:32.017 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
who were in hard labor then.

17:32.051 --> 17:38.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I have been a student of the
Korean Peninsula
for a long time, ever since I
served there

17:38.557 --> 17:42.294 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as the director of intelligence
for U.S. Forces
Korea in the mid-80s.

17:42.327 --> 17:50.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I had underestimated the
level of paranoia
and the siege mentality that
prevails in Pyongyang.

17:50.269 --> 17:55.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, as they look out outward,
all they see
are enemies.

17:55.674 --> 17:58.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so they're not going to give
up their
nuclear weapons.

17:58.777 --> 18:02.915 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, you're
going to be in
South Korea in coming days.

18:02.948 --> 18:06.218 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do you think the best
approach is for
the United States?

18:06.251 --> 18:08.187 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: Well, I think
dialogue.

18:08.220 --> 18:13.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I know we have had --
there's a long history
here of dialogue which hasn't
turned out so

18:13.659 --> 18:15.160 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
well with the North Koreans.

18:15.194 --> 18:17.896 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I attempted it myself.

18:17.930 --> 18:24.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think that's a far better
option than
a military confrontation, which
I think would

18:24.903 --> 18:26.505 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be a disaster.

18:26.538 --> 18:28.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And how much does
it matter
what the president says and
tweets?

18:28.740 --> 18:31.643 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: Well, it matters
a lot.

18:31.677 --> 18:32.778 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Words count.

18:32.811 --> 18:36.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's quite important what he
says or doesn't
say.

18:36.348 --> 18:39.685 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: One final
question about Robert
Mueller.

18:39.718 --> 18:45.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know him well, named special
counsel to
oversee the Russia
investigation.

18:45.491 --> 18:48.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How confident are you that he's
going to be
able to get to the bottom of
what happened?

18:48.894 --> 18:53.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: I think that was
an inspired,
brilliant choice to pick Bob
Mueller for that

18:54.032 --> 18:55.801 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
function.

18:55.834 --> 19:01.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In my opinion, he's cut from the
same cloth
as Jim Comey, two outstanding
public servants.

19:01.974 --> 19:08.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Bob will get to the bottom
of this, and
he will not be intimidated by
any outside

19:08.113 --> 19:09.948 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
influences.

19:09.982 --> 19:13.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: James Clapper,
former director
of national intelligence, thank
you very much.

19:13.719 --> 19:17.055 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JAMES CLAPPER: Thank you.

19:17.089 --> 19:29.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We return our
focus to the
White House, how the Trump
administration

19:29.468 --> 19:35.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is responding to mounting
tensions, and how
that compares to past
administrations, with

19:35.040 --> 19:39.678 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Gerald Seib, executive
Washington editor for
The Wall Street Journal.

19:39.711 --> 19:45.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Christopher Ruddy, he's the
CEO of the
conservative Newsmax media and a
friend of

19:45.184 --> 19:46.685 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
President Trump.

19:46.718 --> 19:48.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And welcome, both of you, to the
program.

19:48.921 --> 19:50.622 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Chris Ruddy, I'm going to start
with you.

19:50.656 --> 19:54.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You told The Wall Street Journal
for their
today's editions that right now
the White

19:54.092 --> 19:58.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
House is in a what you call
perpetual quagmire
on side issues.

19:58.931 --> 20:00.666 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What did you mean by that?

20:00.699 --> 20:04.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER RUDDY, CEO, Newsmax:
Well, the
side issues are things you have
been talking

20:04.603 --> 20:08.440 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about, Judy, and a lot of the
other media
on the Russia issue.

20:08.473 --> 20:14.012 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sometimes, the president's
tweets cause some
of those side issues.

20:14.046 --> 20:19.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they're not focusing on the
-- I think
the big agenda items of the
Trump administration

20:19.451 --> 20:26.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that are very positive for him,
such as his
jobs programs and efforts there,
the fact

20:26.458 --> 20:31.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that he is getting China to open
up its markets
for the first time in 30 years
to American

20:31.930 --> 20:38.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
businesses, incredible movement
on making
the country more secure.

20:38.337 --> 20:42.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those things are not being
talked about,
and they're focusing on
personnel issues and

20:42.507 --> 20:47.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
other things that are not
necessarily moving
their agenda or making the
president more

20:47.980 --> 20:49.715 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
popular.

20:49.748 --> 20:50.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Jerry Seib, how
do you see
the state of affairs right now
in the White

20:50.949 --> 20:52.751 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
House?

20:52.784 --> 20:54.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GERALD SEIB, The Wall Street
Journal: Well,
I think there is a danger at a
time like this

20:54.653 --> 20:58.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the controversy, the
scandal, the investigation
swallows up to the rest of the
agenda.

20:58.724 --> 21:03.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we saw this -- I think back
to the Reagan
White House in the second term,
the Iran-Contra

21:03.462 --> 21:04.429 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
scandal.

21:04.463 --> 21:06.164 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You saw it, as well as I did.

21:06.198 --> 21:09.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there was a real danger that
the whole
second term could be swallowed
up by that

21:09.234 --> 21:11.270 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
scandal, and so the White House
moved.

21:11.303 --> 21:13.071 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It brought in new blood.

21:13.105 --> 21:15.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It brought in a new chief of
staff, a new
White House counsel, a new
national security

21:15.407 --> 21:17.342 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
adviser.

21:17.376 --> 21:21.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, importantly, it set up an
entire separate
channel to handle the
investigation, the scandal,

21:21.446 --> 21:25.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the controversy, trying to wall
off the rest
of the agenda, so it wouldn't
get consumed,

21:25.517 --> 21:28.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and so the rest of the White
House staff could
work on things other than the
scandal that

21:28.987 --> 21:30.789 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
seemed to be everywhere.

21:30.822 --> 21:34.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It took a long while, and people
who worked
in that White House think they
lost almost

21:34.526 --> 21:38.463 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
an entire year to the
controversy, but eventually
they figured out how to get some
other things

21:38.497 --> 21:40.165 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
done.

21:40.198 --> 21:42.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that's in many ways the
challenge
before the Trump White House
right now.

21:42.701 --> 21:46.738 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Chris Ruddy, you
