40:25.156 --> 40:27.358 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
some of Dr. Welch's past
practices.

40:27.391 --> 40:36.434 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," in New
York, I'm William
Brangham.

40:36.467 --> 40:51.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We turn now to
another health
care story, this one the ongoing
political

40:51.215 --> 40:53.851 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
battle to replace Obamacare.

40:53.884 --> 40:58.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. Senate is beginning to
write its
own reform bill, and discovering
there are

40:58.122 --> 41:02.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some big differences of opinion
over what
Republicans passed in the House.

41:02.526 --> 41:07.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Earlier this month, we spoke
with Democratic
Governor John Hickenlooper of
Colorado about

41:07.398 --> 41:10.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
efforts to replace the
Affordable Care Act.

41:10.100 --> 41:11.936 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Today, we hear from a
Republican.

41:11.969 --> 41:13.804 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And our Lisa Desjardins has
that.

41:13.838 --> 41:17.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: As part of our
ongoing look
at what's at stake in health
care for those

41:17.708 --> 41:21.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
closest to the problem, we're
now joined by
Asa Hutchinson, the Republican
governor from

41:21.946 --> 41:23.747 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Arkansas.

41:23.781 --> 41:27.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our viewers will recall that
Arkansas was,
of course, one of the states to
expand Medicaid

41:27.551 --> 41:28.619 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
under Obamacare.

41:28.652 --> 41:31.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Governor Hutchinson, thank you
for joining
us.

41:31.956 --> 41:33.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, you're in an interesting
position.

41:33.757 --> 41:37.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have opposed the Affordable
Care Act,
but also you and your
predecessor, as we just

41:37.828 --> 41:40.097 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
said, supported the expansion.

41:40.130 --> 41:44.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And because of those things, we
have seen
uninsurance rates in your state
get slashed

41:44.401 --> 41:46.770 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in half under the Affordable
Care Act.

41:46.804 --> 41:48.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
What do you think of the
Affordable Care Act
right now?

41:48.839 --> 41:50.107 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Does it need full repeal?

41:50.140 --> 41:51.542 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

41:51.575 --> 41:54.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ASA HUTCHINSON (R), Arkansas:
Well, we need
to change what we have.

41:54.211 --> 41:56.113 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It doesn't work completely.

41:56.146 --> 42:03.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For example, we wanted to reform
the Medicaid
expansion in Arkansas with a
simple work requirement,

42:03.621 --> 42:09.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just lick we have on the SNAP
program, but
under Obamacare, the previous
administration

42:09.326 --> 42:11.228 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
wouldn't give us that
requirement.

42:11.262 --> 42:13.597 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We needed to control the cost
more.

42:13.631 --> 42:20.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're unable to do that whenever
it's mandatory
that you cover everybody up to
138 percent

42:20.738 --> 42:22.640 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the federal poverty level.

42:22.673 --> 42:26.577 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And so we're trying to
concentrate limited
resources in Arkansas.

42:26.610 --> 42:29.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't have the flexibility we
need under
the current program.

42:29.547 --> 42:35.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, yes, I supported a change in
it, and I
applaud the House for starting
the debate

42:35.686 --> 42:40.157 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with passing a repeal and a
replacement.

42:40.190 --> 42:45.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we need to obviously do
more, and I'm
looking for the Senate to --
they're starting

42:45.262 --> 42:46.230 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
over.

42:46.263 --> 42:48.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They're drafting it.

42:48.098 --> 42:50.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I hope they listen to the
governors to provide
the flexibility that's needed,
and I hope

42:50.334 --> 42:55.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they take some ideas from
Arkansas as to some
of the good things we have done
in terms of

42:55.940 --> 42:59.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reform, controlling costs, but
also expanding
health care coverage.

42:59.310 --> 43:03.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: One of the
items of flexibility
that House Republicans would
give you is the

43:03.747 --> 43:08.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ability to waive out of some
things like essential
benefits or a cap on the costs
for people

43:09.019 --> 43:11.322 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
who have preexisting conditions.

43:11.355 --> 43:13.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Are those things that you would
want to waive
out of?

43:13.958 --> 43:15.693 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

43:15.726 --> 43:20.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ASA HUTCHINSON: Not necessarily,
but we have
got to be able to have the
flexibility and

43:20.064 --> 43:22.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
options for the state.

43:22.099 --> 43:27.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, for example, on the health
care benefits,
I think the state should be able
to give more

43:27.371 --> 43:29.607 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
flexibility in terms of
coverage.

43:29.640 --> 43:33.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Not everybody wants every
essential health
benefit.

43:33.911 --> 43:39.516 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They might want to have
different options
and a menu of options that suit
their particular

43:39.550 --> 43:41.285 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
needs.

43:41.318 --> 43:44.989 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's give the states the option
to enhance
coverage, to make sure there's
health care

43:45.022 --> 43:50.094 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
options that are out there, but
also the ability
to control costs.

43:50.127 --> 43:52.830 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so we want to look at a menu
of options.

43:52.863 --> 43:56.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We take two options right now in
terms of
reform.

43:56.367 --> 44:02.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We want to be able to reduce it
from 138 percent
of the federal poverty level
down to the poverty

44:02.806 --> 44:08.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
level, so we can concentrate our
limited resources
on those that need it the most,
shift more

44:08.746 --> 44:14.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the exchange, where they will
have support
and coverage, but it will be a
cost-saving

44:14.318 --> 44:17.187 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
measure, both for the state and
the federal
government.

44:17.221 --> 44:20.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These are types of reforms and
flexibility
that will make sense.

44:20.891 --> 44:25.295 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The work requirement is
important to encourage
people to have the training they
need to move

44:25.329 --> 44:30.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up the employment ladder, to
make more money,
but, at the same time, have some
support for

44:30.567 --> 44:31.869 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
health care.

44:31.902 --> 44:33.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These are the reforms we want to
put into
place.

44:33.737 --> 44:37.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Governor, House
Republicans
would offer you more
flexibility, as you say,

44:37.908 --> 44:41.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but they would also cut some of
the Medicaid
funding you get from the
government, and it

44:41.979 --> 44:44.682 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
seems they are increasing
uncertainty.

44:44.715 --> 44:48.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Insurers need to set their rates
for the next
year, and they aren't sure if
they are going

44:48.852 --> 44:52.189 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to get the subsidies that the
president and
Congress control.

44:52.222 --> 44:56.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What does that uncertainty feel
like, and
are you worried about funding
cuts?

44:56.660 --> 44:58.395 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

44:58.429 --> 45:03.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ASA HUTCHINSON: Yes, that's one
of the big
faults of the House bill is that
it's a cost

45:03.033 --> 45:04.535 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
shift to the states.

45:04.568 --> 45:09.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have to absorb more of the
cost to maintain
the same level of coverage.

45:09.406 --> 45:11.508 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We don't need that cost shift to
the states.

45:11.542 --> 45:14.111 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We need to continue a good
federal-state partnership.

45:14.144 --> 45:21.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I'm looking to the Senate to
rewrite that
portion of it, so the
flexibility is good,

45:21.719 --> 45:27.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but you cannot accompany that
with a massive
cost shift to the states that
would leave

45:27.458 --> 45:33.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more and more uninsured, because
the states
cannot absorb that kind of a
burden.

45:33.397 --> 45:38.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the flexibility is an
important part of
it to be able to manage it.

45:38.302 --> 45:40.003 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Two points.

45:40.037 --> 45:44.975 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Under Obamacare, they
underestimated the number
that was going to go on
Medicaid.

45:45.008 --> 45:46.910 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Too many went on Medicaid.

45:46.944 --> 45:52.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They overestimated those that
would go on
the exchange, and there are too
few on the

45:52.049 --> 45:53.183 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
exchange.

45:53.217 --> 45:54.985 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We want to reverse that.

45:55.018 --> 46:00.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And under Arkansas' plan, you're
going to
restrict those that are on the
Medicaid portion

46:00.891 --> 46:06.663 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of it, shift more to the
exchange, and that's
the original design that makes
it more cost-effective

46:06.697 --> 46:07.664 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for the states.

46:07.698 --> 46:09.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: I see.

46:09.399 --> 46:12.169 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Governor Asa Hutchinson,
Republican of Arkansas,
thank you so much for joining
us.

46:12.202 --> 46:13.170 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

46:13.203 --> 46:17.608 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ASA HUTCHINSON: Great to be with
you.

46:17.641 --> 46:29.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight,
a distinct
way of giving students their own
voice.

46:29.052 --> 46:33.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Earlier, we reported on another
violent holiday
weekend in Chicago.

46:33.524 --> 46:36.860 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
More than 50 people were shot
over four days.

46:36.894 --> 46:39.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Last year, more than 4,000 were
shot in the
city.

46:39.797 --> 46:44.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Often, when we talk about the
school system
in Chicago, we hear about too
much violence

46:44.368 --> 46:46.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and too little money.

46:46.303 --> 46:51.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we look at a project
led by the nation's
poet laureate to give kids a way
of creating

46:52.009 --> 46:56.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
meaningful expression about
their lives and
challenges they face.

46:56.613 --> 46:58.315 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown is back with this
report.

46:58.348 --> 47:01.485 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's part of our weekly series
Making the
Grade.

47:01.518 --> 47:10.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The reality of
one ninth grade
girl's life told in the language
of poetry,

47:10.994 --> 47:12.296 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
by Nakia Sales.

47:12.329 --> 47:15.532 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NAKIA SALES, Student: Black kid,
black kid,
you have been shot.

47:15.566 --> 47:18.402 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Black kid, black kid, why you
have to die?

47:18.435 --> 47:20.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Never got to see you walk across
the stage
in a suit and tie.

47:20.470 --> 47:23.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now your momma crying over your
casket, asking
God why.

47:23.373 --> 47:28.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Earlier, at her
West Side Chicago
school, she'd told me how she
came to write

47:28.178 --> 47:29.880 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
her poem.

47:29.913 --> 47:33.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NAKIA SALES: When we came back
from Christmas
break, I had just lost two of my
friends.

47:33.750 --> 47:35.085 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Lost them to
violence?

47:35.118 --> 47:36.787 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NAKIA SALES: Yes.

47:36.820 --> 47:43.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They was walking down the street
one day,
and a car had rolled past, and
they had got

47:43.727 --> 47:45.596 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
shot, both of them, in the head.

47:45.629 --> 47:50.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, when I got back to
school that day,
when I got to writing, "Black
Kid" automatically

47:50.367 --> 47:52.903 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
came to my mind.

47:52.936 --> 47:58.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: This ceremony at
the Harold
Washington Public Library was
the culmination

47:58.609 --> 48:04.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of a year-long pilot program to
bring poetry
into the curriculum of about 40
inner-city

48:04.281 --> 48:14.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chicago high schools and a
chance for students
to read their work for Juan
Felipe Herrera,

48:14.925 --> 48:27.838 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the outgoing U.S. poet laureate.

48:27.871 --> 48:32.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This past year, Herrera ran four
workshops
for ninth grade English
teachers, offering

48:32.809 --> 48:35.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ideas and prompts to encourage
writing.

48:35.846 --> 48:40.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He urged them to choose their
own reading
texts as examples,anything they
thought their

48:40.050 --> 48:41.952 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
students might relate to.

48:41.985 --> 48:47.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Across the city, more than 85
percent of students
in Chicago public schools are
children of

48:47.591 --> 48:50.994 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
color, and most are classified
as economically
disadvantaged.

48:51.028 --> 48:54.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MISSY HUGHES, Teacher, Michele
Clark Magnet
High School: I'm really
intentional about

48:54.231 --> 48:56.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
finding poems that speak to
their experience.

48:56.934 --> 49:01.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Nakia's teacher,
Missy Hughes
of Michele Clark High School,
was one of the

49:01.405 --> 49:03.373 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
instructors who signed up for
the program.

49:03.407 --> 49:09.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MISSY HUGHES: We just saw how
students were
able to tell their story,
because there's

49:09.813 --> 49:13.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like -- there's this mainstream
narrative
out there about who they are and
what their

49:13.250 --> 49:18.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lives are, and that's -- it
doesn't honor
the complexity or the nuances or
really their

49:18.288 --> 49:20.157 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
own voice.

49:20.190 --> 49:25.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Herrera also
pushed the teachers
to find their own voice through
poetry, and

49:25.729 --> 49:27.164 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to read the results out loud.

49:27.197 --> 49:28.699 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MISSY HUGHES: It's intimidating.

49:28.732 --> 49:31.702 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the poet laureate of the
United States.

49:31.735 --> 49:33.503 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It keeps me honest to do it.

49:33.537 --> 49:38.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's really hard to do that, to
go up there
and write something intimate,
most likely

49:38.041 --> 49:42.079 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
about your life and your
experience, and then
to share that work with
everyone.

49:42.112 --> 49:47.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It worked for the
teachers,
and for students like Nakia, who
says poetry

49:48.018 --> 49:50.887 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has already had a huge impact on
her young
life.

49:50.921 --> 49:55.492 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NAKIA SALES: It's a way to get
anger out too,
stress.

49:55.525 --> 49:57.761 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Anything that you got on your
mind, just let
it out on a piece of paper.

49:57.794 --> 50:02.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But just how do
you reach young
people who don't have experience
with poetry?

50:02.132 --> 50:04.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUAN FELIPE HERRERA, U.S. Poet
Laureate: It
may not be in their background,
maybe, in

50:04.201 --> 50:07.004 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
terms of books, having books at
home.

50:07.037 --> 50:08.939 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But they have a lot of stories.

50:08.972 --> 50:14.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the poetry is there, but
it's there rumbling
in the heart and in the blood
and what they

50:14.778 --> 50:18.315 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
see, you know, what they see day
to day.

50:18.348 --> 50:20.450 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we want to bring all that
out.

50:20.484 --> 50:25.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For Herrera, the
nation's first
Mexico-American poet laureate,
the project

50:25.222 --> 50:26.990 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is deeply personal.

50:27.024 --> 50:32.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When we first met two years ago,
he told me
of growing up in California, the
son of migrant

50:32.062 --> 50:33.830 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
workers from Mexico.

50:33.864 --> 50:38.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He spoke only Spanish at first,
an experience
that left him feeling like an
outsider.

50:38.635 --> 50:42.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUAN FELIPE HERRERA: And it
created a lot
of combustion in me, because I
wanted to be

50:42.939 --> 50:47.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
inside society, I wanted to
communicate, I
wanted to have conversations.

50:47.377 --> 50:49.312 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I got to the point where I just
had to explode.

50:49.346 --> 50:54.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Herrera credits
words and poetry
with unlocking his ability to
communicate

50:54.718 --> 50:56.486 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with the larger world.

50:56.520 --> 51:00.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUAN FELIPE HERRERA: That's the
place I found
peace, the place I found
freedom, the place

51:00.791 --> 51:04.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I found my voice, and the place
where I could
construct things.

51:04.094 --> 51:07.364 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That's the hope
for these students
as well.

51:07.397 --> 51:12.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lynette Mendoza is a teacher at
the Marine
Leadership Academy, a public
school where

51:12.169 --> 51:16.840 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
students prepare for military
service and
wear uniforms.

51:16.873 --> 51:22.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When the laureate visited the
school, Mendoza
says, it had a strong impact on
her students,

51:22.379 --> 51:24.247 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more than 90 percent of whom are
Latino.

51:24.281 --> 51:27.684 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LYNETTE MENDOZA, Marine
Leadership Academy:
They have a male military
instructor, and

51:27.717 --> 51:30.353 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
some of them come from homes
where it's male-dominated.

51:30.387 --> 51:36.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was really important for the
kids to see
a man could read poetry, write
poetry, and

51:36.493 --> 51:38.428 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be inspired and still be a man.

51:38.462 --> 51:39.696 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: That was
important, that he
was a man?

51:39.729 --> 51:41.498 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LYNETTE MENDOZA: I felt it was
real important.

51:41.531 --> 51:45.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But you're making
-- make the
connection from what they learn
from poetry,

51:45.802 --> 51:48.872 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to a science class, or a math
class, or a
government class.

51:48.905 --> 51:52.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LYNETTE MENDOZA: You're looking
at the formulas
in math or in science, that's
the power.

51:52.342 --> 51:58.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you know how to work it,
you know how
to make certain adjustments, you
can come

51:58.148 --> 52:00.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
up with something
earth-shattering.

52:00.083 --> 52:01.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the same thing happens with
words.

52:01.885 --> 52:04.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The district
partnered with
the Library of Congress, which
selects the

52:04.988 --> 52:10.660 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
poet laureate, and the
Chicago-based Poetry
Foundation, which, for the
record, also supports

52:10.694 --> 52:12.095 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the "NewsHour."

52:12.129 --> 52:15.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This remains a small program,
and costs have
been minimal.

52:15.599 --> 52:20.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The school system provides subs
to fill in
when teachers have their
workshop days with

52:20.170 --> 52:21.471 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Herrera.

52:21.505 --> 52:27.711 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LaTanya McDade heads the Office
of Teaching
and Learning.

52:27.744 --> 52:33.617 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And while she admits the
district, the third
largest in the nation, faces
enormous challenges,

52:33.650 --> 52:36.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
getting buy-in for a poetry
program wasn't
one of them.

52:36.419 --> 52:39.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LATANYA MCDADE, Office of
Teaching and Learning:
If you look over time at schools
that have

52:39.389 --> 52:43.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
